Brexit, and then what?
NEW YORK – It will take a long time for the United Kingdom, Europe, and the world to digest the implications of the referendum on "Brexit" conducted by the UK.
The most profound consequences will, of course, depend on the European Union's response to the UK's withdrawal.
Most people initially believed that the EU would not "cut the branch it was sitting on": after all, a friendly divorce seems to be in everyone's interest.
But the divorce— as is often the case— could become complicated.
The benefits of commercial and economic integration between the United Kingdom and the EU are mutual, and if the EU were to take seriously its belief that greater economic integration is desirable, its leaders would seek to ensure that the ties remain as close as possible given the circumstances.
Or, Jean-Claude Juncker, the architect of massive tax avoidance schemes benefiting Luxembourgish companies and now President of the European Commission, seems to be taking a hard line: "Out means out," he said.
This instinctive reaction may be understandable, considering that Juncker might be seen as the one who presided over the first stage of the EU's dissolution.
He argues that, in order to discourage other countries from leaving, the EU must not accept any compromises, offering the UK barely more than what is guaranteed by World Trade Organization agreements.
In other words, Europe should not be kept united by the advantages it offers its members, which far exceed its costs.
According to Juncker, economic prosperity, a sense of solidarity, and pride in being European are not enough.
No, Europe must be maintained through threats, intimidation, and fear.
This position fails to take into account a lesson that appears clearly both in the vote in favor of Brexit and in the Republican Party primaries in the United States: a significant portion of the population has suffered greatly in recent times.
The neoliberal agenda of the last four decades may have been good for the top 1%, but not for the rest of the population.
I had predicted long ago that this stagnation would eventually have political consequences.
This day has now arrived.
On both sides of the Atlantic, citizens believe that trade agreements are the source of their misfortunes.
Although it is an excessive simplification, it is understandable.
Today's trade agreements are negotiated in secret, ensuring good representation of corporate interests but completely excluding ordinary citizens or workers.
As expected, the results were one-sided: the workers' bargaining position has further weakened, thereby exacerbating the effects of legislation that reduces the influence of unions and employees' rights.
Although trade agreements have played a role in creating these inequalities, many other factors have contributed to tipping the political balance in favor of capital.
For example, intellectual property rules have increased the power of pharmaceutical companies to raise prices.
Or, any increase in the market power of firms implies, in fact, a decrease in real wages — an increase in inequalities that has become a characteristic of most advanced countries today.
In many sectors, industrial concentration is increasing – and so is market power.
The effects of stagnation and the decline in real wages have compounded those of austerity, which threatened cuts in public services on which so many low- and middle-income workers depend.
The economic uncertainty resulting for workers, when combined with migration, has created a toxic mix.
Many refugees are victims of wars and oppression to which the West has contributed.
Providing aid is a moral responsibility for all, but especially for former colonial powers.
And yet, although many would probably deny it, an increase in the supply of unskilled labor leads—so long as we are dealing with normal negatively sloped demand curves—to a decrease in equilibrium wages.
And when wages cannot decrease, unemployment increases.
This is particularly concerning in countries where poor economic management has already led to a high level of overall unemployment.
Europe, particularly the eurozone, has been very poorly managed over the past few decades, to the point that its average unemployment rate is now in double digits.
Un free movement in Europe means that countries which have more successfully reduced unemployment will predictably end up hosting more than their fair share of refugees.
Workers in these countries bear the cost of suppressed wages and higher unemployment, while employers benefit from cheaper labor.
As expected, the burden of refugees is borne by those least able to bear it.
Of course, there are many speeches about the net benefits of immigration.
For a country offering a low level of guaranteed benefits—social protection, education, healthcare, etc.—to all its citizens, this can be the case.
But, for countries that provide a decent social safety net, the opposite is true.
The result of all this downward pressure on wages and cuts in public services has been the hollowing out of the middle class, with similar consequences on both sides of the Atlantic.
Middle-class and working-class households have not benefited from economic growth.
They understand that banks caused the 2008 crisis; but then they saw billions allocated to bail out the banks, and insignificant amounts to save their homes and jobs.
While the real (inflation-adjusted) median income for a full-time male worker in the United States is lower than it was four decades ago, the electorate's anger should come as no surprise.
Moreover, the politicians who promised change have not met expectations.
Ordinary citizens knew the system was unjust, but they began to see it as even more rigged than they had imagined, thereby losing whatever remaining trust they had in the ability or will of traditional politicians to correct it.
This is also understandable: the new politicians shared the views of those who had promised that globalization would be beneficial for everyone.
However, a vote of anger does not solve problems, and could instead lead to a political and economic situation that is even worse.
The same applies if one responds with anger to a vote.
Forgetting the past is a basic principle in economics.
On both sides of the Channel, politics must now seek to understand how, in a democracy, the political establishment could have done so little to address the concerns of many citizens.
Each EU government must now consider improving the well-being of ordinary citizens as its primary objective.
More neoliberal ideology will not help.
And we should stop confusing goals with means: for example, free trade, if well managed, could bring greater shared prosperity; but if poorly managed, it will certainly reduce the living standards of many—perhaps even the majority—of citizens.
There are alternatives to the current neoliberal arrangements that can create shared prosperity, just as there are alternatives—such as the Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership with the EU proposed by American President Barack Obama—that would cause far more harm.
The challenge today is to learn from the past in order to adopt the former and avoid the latter.
